sia|Region]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Belgorod Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast|Alexeyevsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      =\n| population_as_of      = \n| population_footnotes  = \n| population_total      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          =\n|utc_offset1_DST        =\n|postal_code_type       =\n|postal_code            =\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_footnotes    =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|50|45|N|38|43|E|display=inline}}\n}}\n'''Gorodishche''' ({{lang-ru|\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0449\u0435}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|khutor]]) in [[Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast|Alexeyevsky District]], [[Belgorod Oblast]], Russia. The population was 56 as of 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf |title=\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 2010 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c. 15. \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0451\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043f\u0443\u043d\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432 |access-date=2019-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123111143/http://belg.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/belg/resources/eab54e804ff0fbbca305efd8c740ec4f/pub-01-15.pdf |archive-date=2018-11-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are 3 streets.<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/belgorodskaya-oblast/alekseevskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Belgorod Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Alexeyevsky District, Belgorod Oblast]]\n\n\n{{BelgorodOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gorodishche,_Alexeyevsky_District,_Belgorod_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "George Cartwright (soldier)", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= George Cartwright\n|image= George Cartwright P01383.010.JPG\n|image_size= 220\n|alt= \n|caption= George Cartwright c.1919\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|1894|12|09|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[South Kensington]], [[London]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1978|02|02|1894|12|09|df=yes}}\n|death_place= [[Gordon, New South Wales|Gordon]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= Australia\n|branch= [[Australian Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1915\u201346\n|rank= [[Captain (land)|Captain]]\n|unit= \n|commands= \n|battles= First World War\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]\n* [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n* [[Hundred Days Offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Mont St. Quentin]]\n* [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal]]\n[[Second World War]]\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]<br/>[[Efficiency Decoration]]<ref name=IWM>{{cite web |url=http://m.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008573 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106034441/http://m.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008573 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2014 |title=Efficiency Decoration ED (OMD 2395) |publisher=[[Imperial War Museum]] |work=Collection Search |accessdate=5 January 2014 }}</ref>\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''George Cartwright''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|VC|ED}} (9 December 1894&nbsp;\u2013 2 February 1978) was a British-born [[List of Australian Victoria Cross recipients|Australian recipient]] of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces. He was one of 64 Australians to receive the award for their actions during the First World War, performing the deeds that led to his award in September 1918 during the [[Battle of Mont Saint-Quentin]] while serving with [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. After the war, Cartwright returned to Australia and worked as a mechanic. He continued to serve in the military part-time, returning to full-time service during the Second World War, undertaking a training role in Australia. He was demobilised in 1946, and returned to civilian life. He died at the age of 83.\n\n==Early life==\nCartwright was born in [[South Kensington]], [[London]], on 9 December 1894 to William Edward Cartwright, a coach trimmer, and his wife Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Stracey).<ref name=\"ADB\">{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Staunton|first=Anthony|year=1993|id=A130422b|title=Cartwright, George (1894\u20131978)|accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref> He attended the local school,<ref name=\"VCs98\">{{Harvnb|Gliddon|2000|p=98}}</ref> before emigrating to Australia in 1912 at the age of eighteen without his family. Settling in [[New South Wales]], Cartwright gained employment at a sheep station in the [[Elsmore, New South Wales|Elsmore]] district as a labourer.<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n\n==First World War==\nOn 9 December 1915\u2014his 21st birthday\u2014Cartwright enlisted in the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] for service during the [[First World War]]. Allotted to the newly raised [[33rd Battalion (Australia)|33rd Battalion]]\u2014an infantry battalion raised in New South Wales\u2014as a [[Private (rank)|private]], he embarked aboard HMAT ''Marathon'' at [[Sydney]] on 4 May 1916.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/awm8/23_50_1/pdf/0121.pdf|title=George Cartwright|accessdate=28 February 2009|work=First World War Embarkation Roll|publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]]}}</ref><ref name=AIFproject>{{cite web |url=http://www.aif.adfa.edu.au:8080/showPerson?pid=48235 |title=George Cartwright|work=The AIF Project |publisher=aif.adfa.edu.au |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227062843/http://www.aif.adfa.edu.au:8080/showPerson?pid=48235 |archivedate=27 February 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> Disembarking at [[Devonport, England|Devonport]], [[England]], two months later,<ref name=\"ServRec\">{{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/114676 |title=George Cartwright \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> the members of the 33rd Battalion spent the following four months training at [[Larkhill Camp]] on [[Salisbury Plain]].<ref name=\"VCs98\"/><ref name=\"33rd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11220.asp|title=33rd Battalion|accessdate=28 February 2009|work=First World War, 1914\u20131918 units |publisher=Australian War Memorial}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[3rd Division (Australia)|3rd Division]], to which the 33rd Battalion was assigned, deployed to the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in November 1916, Cartwright served with them through the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] where he was wounded in June 1917. Later, in April 1918, he was wounded again when the 33rd Battalion's position was attacked with gas while holding a position around [[Villers-Bretonneux]].<ref name=Bomford73>{{Harvnb|Bomford|2012|p=73}}</ref> He was briefly hospitalised but returned to duty in June.<ref name=ADB/> In August, the Allies launched the [[Hundred Days Offensive]] around [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Amiens]], which resulted in a series of advances as the Allies sought to break through the [[Hindenburg Line]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bomford|2012|pp=1\u20133}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 1918, at Road Wood, south-west of [[Bouchavesnes]], near Peronne, [[France]], when two companies became held up by machine gun fire, Cartwright attacked the gun alone under intense fire. He shot three of the crew, and, having bombed the post, captured the gun and nine enemy soldiers. For his actions he was recommended for the Victoria Cross.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31067|date=13 December 1918 |page=14779|supp=y }}</ref> On 30 September 1918 he was wounded and evacuated to England.<ref name=Bomford73/> Cartwright was conferred with his VC by King [[George V]], and at the end of the war Cartwright was repatriated to Australia, arriving in March 1919 and as the AIF was demobilised, he was discharged on 16 May 1919.<ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=AIFproject/> For his war service he received the following medals: the Victoria Cross, the [[British War Medal]] and the [[Victory Medal (United Kingdom)|Victory Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/cartwright-vc.htm|title=Pte George Cartwright VC|accessdate=5 January 2014|work=VC Recipients|publisher=Diggerhistory.info |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126130719/http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/cartwright-vc.htm|archivedate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Inter-war years and Second World War==\nDuring the inter-war years, Cartwright moved to Sydney, where he found work as a motor mechanic. He married Elsie Broker at St Stephen's Anglican Church, at [[Chatswood, New South Wales]], on 25 June 1921. They later had two children, but the marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> He remained in the military, serving part-time in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]], posted to the 4th/3rd Battalion, eventually being commissioned as an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] on 25 February 1932.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> Following the outbreak of the Second World War, Cartwright was mobilised for war service on 5 March 1940, serving in a training role in Australia. He was promoted to [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] in 1942, and served throughout the war.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> In addition to the decorations he received for his previous service, Cartwright also later received the [[Efficiency Decoration]] and the [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]].<ref name=IWM/>\n\n==Later life==\nAfter the war, Cartwright was demobilised in May 1946. He later worked as an assistant-cashier and in 1948 remarried, exchanging nuptials with Evelyn Mary Short on 4 September 1948 in the Congregational Church, at Pitt Street in Sydney. During his later life, he attended several functions held in London for Victoria Cross and George Cross recipients. He died at the age of 84 on 2 February 1978, at [[Gordon, New South Wales]]; his wife and one of his children survived him.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> He was cremated and his Victoria Cross and other decorations were later donated by his widow to the [[Imperial War Museum]] in London, where they are currently held.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Imperial War Museum |url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008566 |title=Victoria Cross (OMD 2387) |accessdate=26 August 2012 |work=Collection Search}}</ref>\n\nCartwright is commemorated in the New South Wales Garden of Remembrance, at [[Rookwood, New South Wales|Rookwood]],<ref name=\"ADB\"/> and also at the Kurrajong Memorial in [[Inverell, New South Wales]], which was unveiled in 2005 in honour of the 114 men from the town who enlisted in January 1916.<ref name=Bomford73/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Bomford |first=Michelle |title=The Battle of Mont St Quentin\u2013Peronne 1918 |series=Australian Army Campaigns Series # 11 |year= 2012 |publisher=Big Sky Publishing |location=Newport, New South Wales |isbn=978-1-921941962 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=The Road to Victory 1918|series=VCs of the First World War|year=2000|publisher=Sutton Publishing Limited|location=Sparkford, England|isbn=0-7509-2083-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/114676 |title=George Cartwright \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}\n* {{Lives of WWI | id= 7384568 | name= George Cartwright }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Staunton|first=Anthony|title=Victoria Cross: Australia's Finest and the Battles they Fought|year=2005|publisher=Hardie Grant Books|location=Prahran, Victoria|isbn=1-74066-288-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartwright, George}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:People from South Kensington]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name= George Cartwright\n|image= George Cartwright P01383.010.JPG\n|image_size= 220\n|alt= \n|caption= George Cartwright c.1919\n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{birth date|1894|12|09|df=yes}}\n|birth_place= [[South Kensington]], [[London]], England\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1978|02|02|1894|12|09|df=yes}}\n|death_place= [[Gordon, New South Wales|Gordon]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= Australia\n|branch= [[Australian Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1915\u201346\n|rank= [[Captain (land)|Captain]]\n|unit= \n|commands= \n|battles= First World War\n* [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]\n* [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]]\n* [[Hundred Days Offensive]]\n* [[Battle of Mont St. Quentin]]\n* [[Battle of St. Quentin Canal]]\n[[Second World War]]\n|awards= [[Victoria Cross]]<br/>[[Efficiency Decoration]]<ref name=IWM>{{cite web |url=http://m.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008573 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106034441/http://m.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008573 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 January 2014 |title=Efficiency Decoration ED (OMD 2395) |publisher=[[Imperial War Museum]] |work=Collection Search |accessdate=5 January 2014 }}</ref>\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''George Cartwright''', {{postnominals|country=AUS|size=100%|sep=,|VC|ED}} (9 December 1894&nbsp;\u2013 2 February 1978) was a British-born [[List of Australian Victoria Cross recipients|Australian recipient]] of the [[Victoria Cross]], the highest award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to British and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] forces. He was one of 64 Australians to receive the award for their actions during the First World War, performing the deeds that led to his award in September 1918 during the [[Battle of Mont Saint-Quentin]] while serving with [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] on the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. After the war, Cartwright returned to Australia and worked as a mechanic. He continued to serve in the military part-time, returning to full-time service during the Second World War, undertaking a training role in Australia. He was demobilised in 1946, and returned to civilian life. He died at the age of 83.\n\n==Early life==\nCartwright was born in [[South Kensington]], [[London]], on 9 December 1894 to William Edward Cartwright, a coach trimmer, and his wife Elizabeth (n\u00e9e Stracey).<ref name=\"ADB\">{{Australian Dictionary of Biography|last=Staunton|first=Anthony|year=1993|id=A130422b|title=Cartwright, George (1894\u20131978)|accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref> He attended the local school,<ref name=\"VCs98\">{{Harvnb|Gliddon|2000|p=98}}</ref> before emigrating to Australia in 1912 at the age of eighteen without his family. Settling in [[New South Wales]], Cartwright gained employment at a sheep station in the [[Elsmore, New South Wales|Elsmore]] district as a labourer.<ref name=\"ADB\"/>\n\n==First World War==\nOn 9 December 1915\u2014his 21st birthday\u2014Cartwright enlisted in the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] for service during the [[First World War]]. Allotted to the newly raised [[33rd Battalion (Australia)|33rd Battalion]]\u2014an infantry battalion raised in New South Wales\u2014as a [[Private (rank)|private]], he embarked aboard HMAT ''Marathon'' at [[Sydney]] on 4 May 1916.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/cms_images/awm8/23_50_1/pdf/0121.pdf|title=George Cartwright|accessdate=28 February 2009|work=First World War Embarkation Roll|publisher=[[Australian War Memorial]]}}</ref><ref name=AIFproject>{{cite web |url=http://www.aif.adfa.edu.au:8080/showPerson?pid=48235 |title=George Cartwright|work=The AIF Project |publisher=aif.adfa.edu.au |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227062843/http://www.aif.adfa.edu.au:8080/showPerson?pid=48235 |archivedate=27 February 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014}}</ref> Disembarking at [[Devonport, England|Devonport]], [[England]], two months later,<ref name=\"ServRec\">{{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/114676 |title=George Cartwright \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> the members of the 33rd Battalion spent the following four months training at [[Larkhill Camp]] on [[Salisbury Plain]].<ref name=\"VCs98\"/><ref name=\"33rd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11220.asp|title=33rd Battalion|accessdate=28 February 2009|work=First World War, 1914\u20131918 units |publisher=Australian War Memorial}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[3rd Division (Australia)|3rd Division]], to which the 33rd Battalion was assigned, deployed to the [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]] in November 1916, Cartwright served with them through the [[Battle of Messines (1917)|Battle of Messines]] where he was wounded in June 1917. Later, in April 1918, he was wounded again when the 33rd Battalion's position was attacked with gas while holding a position around [[Villers-Bretonneux]].<ref name=Bomford73>{{Harvnb|Bomford|2012|p=73}}</ref> He was briefly hospitalised but returned to duty in June.<ref name=ADB/> In August, the Allies launched the [[Hundred Days Offensive]] around [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Amiens]], which resulted in a series of advances as the Allies sought to break through the [[Hindenburg Line]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Bomford|2012|pp=1\u20133}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 August 1918, at Road Wood, south-west of [[Bouchavesnes]], near Peronne, [[France]], when two companies became held up by machine gun fire, Cartwright attacked the gun alone under intense fire. He shot three of the crew, and, having bombed the post, captured the gun and nine enemy soldiers. For his actions he was recommended for the Victoria Cross.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=31067|date=13 December 1918 |page=14779|supp=y }}</ref> On 30 September 1918 he was wounded and evacuated to England.<ref name=Bomford73/> Cartwright was conferred with his VC by King [[George V]], and at the end of the war Cartwright was repatriated to Australia, arriving in March 1919 and as the AIF was demobilised, he was discharged on 16 May 1919.<ref name=\"ADB\"/><ref name=AIFproject/> For his war service he received the following medals: the Victoria Cross, the [[British War Medal]] and the [[Victory Medal (United Kingdom)|Victory Medal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/cartwright-vc.htm|title=Pte George Cartwright VC|accessdate=5 January 2014|work=VC Recipients|publisher=Diggerhistory.info |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110126130719/http://www.diggerhistory.info/pages-vc/cartwright-vc.htm|archivedate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Inter-war years and Second World War==\nDuring the inter-war years, Cartwright moved to Sydney where he found work as a motor mechanic. He married Elsie Broker at St Stephen's Anglican Church, at [[Chatswood, New South Wales]], on 25 June 1921. They later had two children, but the marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> He remained in the military, serving part-time in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]], posted to the 4th/3rd Battalion, eventually being commissioned as an [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] on 25 February 1932.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> Following the outbreak of the Second World War, Cartwright was mobilised for war service on 5 March 1940, serving in a training role in Australia. He was promoted to [[Captain (land and air)|captain]] in 1942, and served throughout the war.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> In addition to the decorations he received for his previous service, Cartwright also later received the [[Efficiency Decoration]] and the [[War Medal 1939\u20131945]].<ref name=IWM/>\n\n==Later life==\nAfter the war, Cartwright was demobilised in May 1946. He later worked as an assistant-cashier and in 1948 remarried, exchanging nuptials with Evelyn Mary Short on 4 September 1948 in the Congregational Church, at Pitt Street in Sydney. During his later life, he attended several functions held in London for Victoria Cross and George Cross recipients. He died at the age of 84 on 2 February 1978, at [[Gordon, New South Wales]]; his wife and one of his children survived him.<ref name=\"ADB\"/> He was cremated and his Victoria Cross and other decorations were later donated by his widow to the [[Imperial War Museum]] in London, where they are currently held.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Imperial War Museum |url=http://www.iwm.org.uk/collections/item/object/30008566 |title=Victoria Cross (OMD 2387) |accessdate=26 August 2012 |work=Collection Search}}</ref>\n\nCartwright is commemorated in the New South Wales Garden of Remembrance, at [[Rookwood, New South Wales|Rookwood]],<ref name=\"ADB\"/> and also at the Kurrajong Memorial in [[Inverell, New South Wales]], which was unveiled in 2005 in honour of the 114 men from the town who enlisted in January 1916.<ref name=Bomford73/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Bomford |first=Michelle |title=The Battle of Mont St Quentin\u2013Peronne 1918 |series=Australian Army Campaigns Series # 11 |year= 2012 |publisher=Big Sky Publishing |location=Newport, New South Wales |isbn=978-1-921941962 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gliddon|first=Gerald|title=The Road to Victory 1918|series=VCs of the First World War|year=2000|publisher=Sutton Publishing Limited|location=Sparkford, England|isbn=0-7509-2083-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://discoveringanzacs.naa.gov.au/browse/person/114676 |title=George Cartwright \u2013 Discovering Anzacs |publisher=[[National Archives of Australia]] |accessdate=10 October 2014}}\n* {{Lives of WWI | id= 7384568 | name= George Cartwright }}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Staunton|first=Anthony|title=Victoria Cross: Australia's Finest and the Battles they Fought|year=2005|publisher=Hardie Grant Books|location=Prahran, Victoria|isbn=1-74066-288-1}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cartwright, George}}\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Australian military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Australian World War I recipients of the Victoria Cross]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:People from South Kensington]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInter-war years and Second World War:replaced: moved to Sydney \u2192 moved to Sydney,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Cartwright_(soldier)"}
